Netizens Confuse East African plague of locusts with india-pakistan plague of locusts.

The plague of locusts in India and Pakistan will not affect China for the time being, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations told Southern Weekly.

The threat of desert locusts to China is still uncertain, and we should be more alert to the compound pest of noctuid moth and desert locust.

Bird and other animal control methods can only be applied to a small area.

This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Yang Kaiqi, southern weekly reporter

Southern weekend intern, Song Bingchen

Editor in chief | Wang Tao

"400 billion army of locusts" does not seem to come, China has just warmed up, ready to vacate the "plague of locusts" concept shares fell.

On February 14,2020, a number of Chinese media released news that "from Africa into India, Pakistan, " the locust army reached "400 billion. ". Four days later, The Times of India reported that the plague of locusts was largely over, with only a few remaining in parts of Rajasthan.

Just because the frenzy of capital has been quelled does not mean that the public's misunderstanding of the rotifers has been dispelled -- as if by confounding the locusts of East Africa and India and Pakistan, and expecting to see ducks eating locusts... nor does it mean that locusts will never come to China again, you can let your guard down.

Wrong number one
Mixed up two plague of locusts

Wrong number one

Mixed up two plague of locusts

Imagine an army of hundreds of millions descending from the sky, sweeping through the African continent that was the birthplace of Lucy the maiden, heading north across the Mediterranean and Arab civilizations, all the way to the heart of the Mesopotamian civilization, where the crops failed.

What an apocalyptic vision. But did the locusts from India and Pakistan come from Africa? No, netizens mixed up the two plague of locusts.

Although both are desert locusts, east African swarms from the Arabian Peninsula's southern desert began to hatch in large numbers as early as 2018, after several rounds of rapid recruitment, from the Arabian Peninsula to the West, over the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden to the Horn of Africa. The Indian locust plague occurred in the summer of 2019 and lasted until the beginning of 2020. The origin of the population is unknown.

In an e-mailed response to southern weekend, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations said locusts in east Africa were still in their breeding season, not yet at the highest level of "plague, " but could become "plague. ".

Even so, the plague is the worst in the east African countries of Somalia and Ethiopia in 25 years, and the worst in Kenya and Uganda in 70 years. According to FAO's Desert Locust Situation Bulletin (No. 496) released on February 3,2020, there are already 246477 hectares of threatened areas in the world. Failure to take timely and effective measures could lead to a food crisis for 13 million people in East Africa.

But the locusts are still mainly in east Africa, spreading to the Red Sea coast and south-west Asia, where locusts are of concern but have not yet reached their breeding peak.

The Indian and Pakistani locust swarms closer to China, says Keith Cressman, the FAO's senior official in charge of locust alert, are unlikely to affect China because the swarms are now in the western tip of southwest Pakistan, they can not cross the high, cold Himalayas to the north, nor can they cross northern India to the east.

FAO has been using satellites to monitor locust plagues in real time and has been able to provide an early warning to affected countries six weeks in advance. According to the FAO, the situation along the india-pakistan border is stable, with some small locust swarms in the fields of only Punjab, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and Balochistan in Pakistan. In India, the state of Rajasthan has a few remaining locust swarms that breed in the summer and local authorities are conducting control operations.

Truth Number One
The threat is still out there, and you can't let your guard down

Truth Number One

The threat is still out there, and you can't let your guard down

For East African locusts, the FAO warns that "high tides" can turn into "plagues" if not contained in time. "under the right conditions, locust populations can increase 20-fold every three months, 400-fold after six months and 8,000-fold after nine months, threatening food security in more than 30 countries and regions around the world, " noted Keith Cressman

Nor should they let down their guard against Indian and Pakistani locust infestations. Shi Wangpeng, an expert in pest control and a professor of entomology at China Agricultural University, explained that locusts live for only two months. Their mission in life is to breed and their life is nearly over after they lay eggs. The plague of locusts in India is not only due to the effectiveness of government control, but also due to the natural death of locusts after oviposition.

Swarms of locusts that breed in summer have left huge numbers of eggs on the ground in South Asia that can hatch in the right hydrothermal conditions, setting off a new outbreak. Meanwhile, desert locusts continue to breed along the southeast coast of Iran, one of the likely sources of the indo-pakistani plague, "hatching about two months earlier than usual, " the FAO said.

India is bracing for a second generation of locusts in the summer of 2020. Agriculture Minister Kailash Subhasish Roy Chowdhury told The Times of India that the government plans to purchase 60 professional sprayers equipped with the latest technology, using helicopters and drones to spray pesticides from the air.

The government of Pakistan has also launched a level one emergency response. "I've been getting text messages from Pakistan, and the message from Feb. 18 is that the locusts are still flying, " Shi said. "I still can't take it lightly. "

According to the entomologist, China recorded about 796 locust plagues between 707 BC and 1935. The Chinese people have a lot of experience in controlling locusts in the thousand-year war, but the desert locusts are a new challenge for us. "The majority of locusts in China are Asian, Siberian and Italian locusts, " Shi said. "Few people in China have seen this kind of desert locust. ".

This potential enemy may be more formidable than its old rival, the Asian locust. Asian locusts do not eat sweet potatoes, potatoes, hemp and other crops, while desert locusts eat more, reproduce faster, fly better and grow bigger, and eat as much as they weigh each day, is a fill up the speed, the individual soldier quality high army.

For now, the threat to China from desert locusts remains elusive. China is tracking and preparing for a plague of locusts in India and Pakistan.

According to the Hsinking newspaper, the Xinjiang is monitoring the flight path of the swarms in India and Pakistan. An expert told southern weekend that on Feb. 19, the Ministry of Agriculture asked him and agricultural experts to "report on several monitoring sites that can be set up. ".

Compared with the long and arduous "central asia-xinjiang" route, Wang Qiang (not his real name) , a staff member of the Department of Agriculture's planting and Agriculture Administration, worries that the "myanmar-yunnan" route will become the main focus of the desert locusts, in the past, Asian migratory locusts from Myanmar and Laos have invaded Yunnan. Fortunately, prevention and control did not cause a major disaster in time.

However, prior to this, relevant officials of the Department of Crop Management of the Ministry of Agriculture and rural areas had told the media that since southern Tibet and the western border of Yunnan are adjacent to desert locust outbreak areas in Nepal and Myanmar, the possibility of a small number of locusts migrating into China with the monsoon is not ruled out, but the probability of causing harm is very small.

Yunnan locust control departments often "resist locusts outside the country, " to Myanmar, Laos to help the local people jointly control the plague of locusts. Only this time the threat has turned into a desert locust, "and the fact that even India and Pakistan are sitting down to meet about it shows how dire the situation is. ". They judge that due to geographical barriers, desert locusts less likely to invade China, but still with a positive attitude, "is doing supplies and technology reserves. ".

According to Shi Wangpeng, the locusts, commonly known as grasshoppers, generally do not fly in groups and are less harmful than locusts, mainly controlling their spread; locusts need to be killed in their places of origin to avoid their growing in large groups; and for invading locusts, be Sure to hang it at the first stop of the invasion.

Wang Qiang's unit plans to carry out monitoring and early warning of locust plagues abroad, as well as site based contacts with Myanmar and Bangladesh, which are on the likely invasion routes. At present, the Yunnan Provincial Department of Agriculture has drawn up a plan to deal with the desert locust plague, pending a final decision.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Desert locust outbreaks in Kenya (FAO / Photo)

Oolong II
"Using Duck to control locusts" is not the mainstream

Oolong II

"Using Duck to control locusts" is not the mainstream

Xinjiang attracts starlings to hunt locusts, Zhejiang sends 100,000 ducks to Xinjiang to kill locusts... . With the news of the African plague of locusts, there are stories of various birds fighting locusts. Shi says these methods can only be applied to a small area.

The general consensus around the world is to keep locusts away from the NYMPHS and to keep the adults from flocking.

The native locusts in China grow on barren beaches and sandy land. The biological control advocated by the state mainly uses microorganisms, antibiotics and plant salts to kill locust larvae, which is less of an environmental burden. And the invasion of locusts are adults, to kill directly, it must be combined with aircraft, manual, large-scale spraying of pesticides. At present, China has three special airports for locust control in Hebei, Shandong and Xinjiang.

Shi has learned that pesticides used in FAO assistance to Africa are mainly organophosphorus, pyrethroid and Carbamate pesticides. China's pesticides for Asian locusts are similar, and some of the more toxic ones have been phased out for safety reasons. "On the whole, China has a relatively sufficient reserve of materials to deal with the plague of locusts, and its technology is at the leading level in the world. We can rest assured. "

The more radical strategy is to compress the locusts'spawning grounds directly, because they can only lay their eggs on bare land, and the more vegetation there is, the harder it is for the locusts to grow. China has not had a large-scale plague of locusts for many years.

In fact, not only China, affected by the desert locust plague in South Asia, West Asia, East Africa has not seen such a large-scale plague of locusts for a long time. The last plague of locusts in Pakistan was in 1993. "I've been to Pakistan to give a talk, and the new generation there hasn't had much locust plague, " Shi said.

Fact number two
To be on guard against the compound insect disaster of NOCTUID moth and desert locust

Fact number two

To be on guard against the compound insect disaster of NOCTUID moth and desert locust

Once the desert locusts do invade, some of the lessons that have worked for Asian locusts need to be adjusted.

Adjusting the planting structure, that is, planting crops that the locusts do not like to eat, was once an effective response to the plague of locusts. The locusts were abundant in southern China until the founding ceremony of the People's Republic of China transformed some of the locust prone areas of Florida, especially the rice fields around the Great Lakes, into Alfalfa, thus greatly reducing the plague of locusts. But desert locusts have a complex diet, and finding crops that the species doesn't like is a challenge.

For Wang Qiang, in addition to staring at the desert locusts, there is also the fear that the 2019 invasion of Yunnan's grasslands could lead to a complex infestation of desert locusts.

The meadow moth is also a terrible pest. The insect, which is highly prolific and migratory, is native to the Americas and has spread to more than 100 countries since it was discovered in Africa in 2016. It was listed as a "major migratory agricultural pest" by FAO in August 2018. It is also a variety of food habits, mainly harm corn, eating corn leaves, corn core and pistil. If allowed to spread, the yield of maize could be reduced by 70%-90% .

In 2019, the moth invaded from Hani people, an autonomous county on the border with Vietnam and Laos, forming a local population and some migrating north, Wang Qiang said. As the temperature cools in 2020, the population of the northern meadow moth will return to the south, and Yunnan will be attacked by the invasion population, the local population and the returning population.

Fact number three
Watch out for insect outbreaks triggered by climate change

Fact number three

Watch out for insect outbreaks triggered by climate change

East African and indo-pakistani locust plagues are two different things, but much evidence points to a possible link between localized outbreaks and climate change in recent years.

The source of this plague of locusts in east Africa is a "no man's land" in the Arabian Peninsula desert, an arid wasteland where life is hard to find.

But two tropical cyclones in the Indian Ocean in 2018, "MEKUNA" and "Lu Ban" , brought rare precipitation to the desert, where the sand is saturated with the more moist soil needed for a critical period of desert locust hatching. The desert locusts have multiplied freely for three generations in nine months under suitable and unsupervised conditions, and their numbers have increased 8,000-fold, making them an orgy of breeding.

The FAO told southern weekend that a surge of locusts on such a scale had been "unprecedented" in recent years.

There is necessity in chance. In the past three years, the frequency of cyclones in the Indian Ocean has increased, which plays a role in the large-scale desert locust breeding. Another tropical cyclone in December 2019 triggered another breeding boom, which could lead to two generations of desert locusts breeding as much as 400 times as many as there are now, until June 2020.

How climate change will change the spread and reproduction of pests is hard to predict. "Therefore, although desert locusts are an ancient threat, if the current trend of increasing tropical cyclones continues, the Horn of Africa is likely to experience more outbreaks in the future, " the FAO said in its response to southern weekend.

A report in The Times of India questioned whether locusts should normally appear in July or October, rather than in winter. Experts believe the change in locust habits may be due to the lengthening of the Indian monsoon season and changes in wind direction. Pakistani officials also believe that locusts, which used to migrate to Iran after hatching for some time, may still be present in Pakistan because of low temperatures.

The warm winter of 2019 and the spring drought of 2020 in Yunnan are also "good seasons" for the moth. Faced with the stress of the disaster, Wang Qiang said: "drought is good for insects, but if there is more rain, pests will be less, but crop diseases will be more. " Different meteorological conditions, the need for the agricultural sector to adjust different measures, insects take food.
